# Shell visibility (Li compile & test)

Li work runs **long builds and test suites** often. Agents must not hide whether a process finished or what failed.

## Required

- Run **build / CI / test commands in the foreground** so tool output streams back in the chat.
- After each meaningful step, report **`echo "step exit=$?"`** on its own line (same shell, immediately after the command).
- Prefer **one phase per Shell invocation** (e.g. `build.sh`, then `run_httpd_config.sh`, then `run_all.sh`) instead of one opaque mega-script.
- Use the Shell tool **`block_until_ms`** long enough for compile/test to finish (minutes for full `ci.sh` / `run_all.sh`).

## Forbidden

| Pattern | Why |
|---------|-----|
| `cmd > /tmp/foo.log 2>&1` then `grep`/`tail` the log | Hides live output; easy to miss failure |
| `cmd 2>&1 \| tail -20` (or `head`) as the only check | Truncates errors; pipeline exit may be `tail`'s |
| `cmd \| tee log` when the agent only reads `log` later | Same as redirect if stdout isn't in the tool result |
| Background `cmd &` for compile/test unless the user asked | No clear completion signal |
| `echo exit=$?` after a **pipeline** without `set -o pipefail` | Often prints `0` from `tail`/`tee`, not `cmd` |

## Allowed

- Short filters on **already-finished** output the user asked to summarize (not as the only way to run CI).
- `set -o pipefail` when a pipeline is truly needed; then report the failing command's status.
- `tee` only if **full stdout/stderr still appear** in the Shell tool result (user can see progress).

## Examples

```bash
# BAD — outcome hidden
./scripts/local-ci.sh > /tmp/ci.log 2>&1
grep FAIL /tmp/ci.log | tail -20
echo "exit=$?"

# GOOD — visible + explicit
./scripts/build.sh
echo "build exit=$?"

./li-tests/run_all.sh
echo "run_all exit=$?"
```

Do not substitute log scraping for running the command where the agent and user can see it complete.
